            <entry xml:id="entry_kældæ" xml:lang="os-x-digor">
                <form type="lemma"><orth>kældæ</orth></form>
                <usg><lang/></usg>
                <sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                        <q>валежник</q>
                    </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                        <q>brushwood</q>
                    </abv:tr></sense>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Можно было бы думать о лексикализовэнном причастии от %ikælun%i
                    ‘падать’, ‘валиться’ („упавшее“, „повалившееся“), см. <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_kælyn"/>. Но велик также соблазн связать слово с обширной
                    индоевропейской группой: и.е. %i*k˳ḷdo-%i, <mentioned xml:lang="cu"><lang/>
                        <w n="0">клада</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/>
                        <w>колода</w>
                        <gloss><q>лежачее дерево</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>бревно</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="pl"><lang/>
                        <w>kłoda</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>κλάδος</w>
                        <gloss><q>ветка</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ang"><lang/>
                        <w>holt</w>
                        <gloss><q>лес</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/>
                        <w>Holz</w></mentioned> и пр. (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Berneker"
                            /><biblScope>543</biblScope></bibl>). — К осетинскому примыкает
                        <mentioned xml:lang="krc-x-balkar"><lang/>
                        <w>kəldə</w>
                        <gloss><q>валежник</q></gloss></mentioned>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">It might be a lexicalized participle from %ikælun%i ‘to fall’,
                    ‘to tumble down’ („fallen“, „tumbled“), see <ref type="xr" target="#entry_kælyn"
                    />. However, there is also a great temptation to relate this word to a vast
                    Indo-European group: Indo-European %i*k˳ḷdo-%i, <mentioned xml:lang="cu"><lang/>
                        <w>klada</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/>
                        <w>колода</w>
                        <gloss><q>lying tree</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>log</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="pl"><lang/>
                        <w>kłoda</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/>
                        <w>κλάδος</w>
                        <gloss><q>branch</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ang"><lang/>
                        <w>holt</w>
                        <gloss><q>forest</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="de"><lang/>
                        <w>Holz</w></mentioned> etc. (<bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_Berneker"
                            /><biblScope>543</biblScope></bibl>). — <mentioned
                        xml:lang="krc-x-balkar"><lang/>
                        <w>kəldə</w>
                        <gloss><q>brushwood</q></gloss></mentioned> is also related to
                    Ossetic.</etym>
            </entry>
